data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous APIs via an explicit opt-in (sync-over-async). **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All four of your synchronous calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime:

| Sync (now throws) | Async replacement |
|-|-|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | `FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Required Fix

Convert the repository to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- The Cosmos DB provider never had true sync support — it was always wrapping async calls internally, which risks deadlocks.
- `async`/`await` will propagate up through your call chain, so callers of this repository must also become async.
- You can also remove the now-obsolete sync-over-async opt-in from your `DbContext` configuration.
